I dont think that will work.  Since our exceptionhandler uses sys.exit(), i dont think the exception block with execute since the process will die before a return.  If you want to be able to handle a failed call, we will need to use a flag to redirect the exception.  (i think this was your idea when we were talking about it earlier)  Something like this:

```
	def call_process(self, cmd, returnexception=False):
        if not isinstance(cmd, list):
            exceptionhandler('Command is not a list.\n{0}'.format(str(cmd)))
        process = subprocess.Popen(cmd, stdout=subprocess.PIPE, stderr=subprocess.PIPE)
        out, err = process.communicate()
        if process.returncode != 0 and returnexception:
            return subprocess.CalledProcessError, err
        elif process.returncode !=0:
            exceptionhandler('Command execution failed.\n{0}\nError Message:{1}'.format(cmd, err)
        else:
            logging.info(out)
```

nit: can we avoid variable declaration in middle of method? 

Possible solution to  define a private method to get the frame:
```
Frame &MacGetTxFrame(void)  
{
    Frame *frame = NULL;

    switch (mOperation)
     {
     case kOperationTransmitOutOfBandFrame:
         frame = mOobFrame;
         break;
 
     default:
         frame = mTxFrame;
         break;
     }

    return *frame;
}
````
And then from `Mac::HandleBeginTransmit()` we do 
```
    Frame &sendFrame = GetTxFrame();

@nthykier OK, changes were minimal (basically I decided to discard my previous idea and strip newlines unconditionally (as suggested in the spec but not applied by Firefox unfortunately).

Regarding usage of regular expressions: I did some tests and it turns out `string.replace()` is usually faster than a re. Especially for short strings (and we have to consider white-space only text nodes here, too!) it clearly wins. Even for longs strings the regular expressions does not give an advantage. Only for examples that shouldn't be common in practice (long strings with many consecutive spaces) the re seems to give a small advantage. Feel free to cross-check my findings if you want (maybe even on some real world data)!

Please note we can *not* call `.strip(' ')` unconditionally, as for example `<text>text <tspan>tspan</tspan> text</text>` should result in "text text text" as the whole "character data" of the text node is to be processed in one step and not as individual childs (that's what I gathered from an IRC discussion I had with Tavmjong Bah on IRC yesterday).

